        "#### Popularity Bias"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "44240096",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "In music datasets, global hits (e.g., a Taylor Swift or The Weeknd track) act as statistical magnets. Because their \"Support($B$)\" is naturally high, the \"Confidence($A \\rightarrow B$)\" will almost always be high, regardless of what item $A$ is. Lift corrects this by dividing the Confidence by the probability of $B$ occurring anyway. It is calculated as the ratio of the observed support to the expected support if the two items were completely independent. \n",
        "$$\\text{(eq 1)}: \\text{Lift}(A \\rightarrow B) = \\frac{\\text{Confidence}(A \\rightarrow B)}{\\text{Support($B$})}.$$\n",
        "The value of Lift is generally interpreted against a baseline of 1:\n",
        "- Lift > 1 means that there is a positive correlation. \n",
        "- Lift = 1 implies no relationship between A and B.\n",
        "- Lift < 1 indicate a negative or inverse association. In this case, the presence of the A decreases the likelihood of B.\n",
        "\n",
        "The average lift across all cluster is printed below."
>>>>>>> e001c4ecd6146b10c684101d909dea0cf00f7607
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "d7bf96a5",
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
